        "text": ". ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "He is not the God of the dead, but of the living ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "— That is, (if the argument be proposed at length,) since the character of his being the God of any persons, plainly intimates a relation to them, not as dead, but as living; and since he cannot be said to be at present their God at all, if they are utterly dead; nor to be the God of human persons, such as Abraham, Isaac, and Jacob, consisting of souls and bodies, if their bodies were to abide in everlasting death; there must needs be a future state of blessedness, and a resurrection of the body, to share with the soul in it.",
        "children": []
      },
